`crates/ctx-scan/src` is the whole `ctx-scan` binary and library: walk an arbitrary directory, maintain a content-hash-based `.context/` mirror of summaries, and expose four operations (scan, check, prune, update) plus a stop-hook mode, each reachable both as a library entry point (`runner::*_run`) and a CLI flag (`cli::dispatch`). Depending on this crate gets you hash-based staleness detection that's independent of git, orphan cleanup for deleted sources, and a machine-readable `--contract` string kept in sync with actual CLI behavior via a test.

The core coupling is the `Staleness`/hash pipeline threading through `hash.rs` → `staleness.rs` → `runner.rs` → `render.rs`: hash.rs computes/diffs the tree and produces `stale_dirs`/`changed_files`/`orphan_leaves`; `record_missing_artifacts` and `reconcile::find_orphan_artifacts` separately populate `missing_artifacts`/`orphan_artifacts` (gaps hash-diffing alone can't see); `Staleness` aggregates all five categories with two predicates (`is_fresh`, `needs_regeneration`) that callers must pick correctly between; `render.rs` prints the five categories in a fixed label order that must match `Staleness`'s field semantics. Any new staleness category has to be threaded through all four files.

`walker.rs` and `reconcile.rs` both define "what's in scope" independently (`.ctxignore` matching vs. `Live::from_targets` built from walker's `targets`) — they must stay consistent or orphan detection silently drifts. `cpath` conventions (referenced from `hash.rs`) define the mirrored `.context/<dir>` layout that `ctx-summarize` also writes to; that layout is a crate-external contract, not owned here. `main.rs` and `cli.rs` split responsibility: `main.rs` picks the mode and constructs the agent only when needed (fail-fast, fail-open for stop-hook), `cli.rs` validates and dispatches into `runner`. `contract.rs`'s constant must be edited whenever any CLI flag behavior changes, enforced by a test comparing it against generated docs.

Invariant spanning the subtree: only `scan_run`/`update_run`'s regeneration path ever constructs an `Agent` or needs credentials; dry-run/check/prune/stop-hook are always filesystem-only.